# INTERVIEW 2 — Yash Sangle
**Role:** IT Risk & Management, Deloitte  
**Duration:** 10 minutes  

Yash works in IT risk and management at Deloitte, where his work focuses on governance, auditing processes, and compliance oversight. His responsibilities involve ensuring transparency, traceability, and accountability in technical systems.

When discussing carbon accounting tools, Yash explained that many existing systems feel **too technical and difficult to understand for non-engineering stakeholders**. Sustainability tools often require users to interpret complex dashboards or technical metrics, which can make them difficult for risk and compliance professionals to engage with.

He expressed that interacting with such a system through **natural language would make the experience significantly easier**. Instead of navigating technical interfaces, he would prefer to ask simple questions such as:

> "What is our carbon footprint?"  
> "What changes would reduce our emissions the most?"

Another important concern he raised was the importance of **auditability and transparency**. In risk and compliance environments, it is critical to understand how numbers are calculated and what data sources were used to generate them.

During the conversation, the topic of carbon credits also came up. Yash mentioned that although the current cost of carbon credits may not seem very high, the rapid growth of AI workloads could make carbon a **much more valuable resource in the future**. If organizations can track and manage carbon credits effectively, he believes they could eventually become **tradeable assets**, similar to financial instruments or commodities.

### Tool Failures Identified
- Carbon tools are difficult for non-technical stakeholders to interpret
- Lack of natural-language interaction with emissions data
- Limited transparency into emissions calculations

### Opportunity for Our Tool
Develop a natural-language AI interface that allows users to **query emissions data, understand calculations, and access audit trails without needing technical expertise**.
